🚀 JavaScript Execution Context (Full Flow Notes)
🧠 JavaScript Basics
⚙️ Synchronous
→ Executes one line at a time
🧵 Single-threaded
→ Only one call stack

👉 Default behavior = Blocking execution
👉 Each operation waits for previous one ⏳

📦 Core Components
1. 🗂️ Call Stack
Stores execution contexts
Works on LIFO (Last In First Out) 🔁
2. 🧠 Memory Heap
Stores variables & objects
⚡ Execution Context

👉 Environment where JS code runs

Types:
🌍 Global Execution Context (GEC)
🧩 Function Execution Context (FEC)
🧪 Eval Execution Context (rare)
🔁 How Code Executes (VERY IMPORTANT FLOW)

Each execution context runs in 2 phases:

🟡 1. Memory Creation Phase (Hoisting Phase)

👉 JS scans code before execution

Variables → undefined
Functions → full definition stored
Example:
let val1 = 10
let val2 = 5

function addNum(num1, num2){
    let total = num1 + num2
    return total
}

let result1 = addNum(val1, val2)
let result2 = addNum(10, 2)
Memory Phase Output:
val1 → undefined
val2 → undefined
addNum → function definition ✅
result1 → undefined
result2 → undefined
🟢 2. Execution Phase

👉 Now actual code runs line by line

val1 = 10
val2 = 5
🔥 Function Call Flow (VERY IMPORTANT)
👉 When addNum(val1, val2) runs:
Step 1: 🆕 New Execution Context Created
New Variable Environment (VE)
New Execution Thread
Step 2: Memory Phase (inside function)
num1 → undefined
num2 → undefined
total → undefined
Step 3: Execution Phase
num1 → 10
num2 → 5
total → 15

👉 Returns 15 🔁

Step 4: 🗑️ Context Deleted
Function EC removed from call stack
🔁 Same happens for:
addNum(10, 2)

Result:

total → 12
